# Agent governance

Adapted from [OWASP Secure Coding with AI Cheat Sheet](https://github.com/OWASP/CheatSheetSeries/blob/master/cheatsheets/Secure_Coding_with_AI_Cheat_Sheet.md) (rules-file stewardship), CloudDefense-style agent guardrails, and anti-sycophancy coding discipline.

## Rules files are security-critical

Treat as CI-level config (prompt-injection / persistent steering surface):

- `.cursor/rules/**`, `.cursorrules`, `.github/copilot-instructions.md`, `AGENTS.md` (if added)
- **Do not** silently weaken security/privacy rules, delete guardrails, or add “ignore security” instructions
- **Do not** modify these files unless the user explicitly asks; summarize intended rule diffs first

## Supply chain & scope

- Ask before adding dependencies or changing CI (`.github/workflows/**`)
- Do not force-push, disable hooks, or run destructive git (`reset --hard`, clean -fd) unless explicitly requested
- Do not edit `package-lock.json` except as a consequence of an approved dependency change via `npm install`/`npm ci`

## Honesty over confidence

- Never invent APIs/signatures; verify against installed versions / docs
- Do not say “looks good” without evidence (read code, run tests, or state what was not verified)
- When urgency is invoked, state the security/privacy trade-off once, then proceed if the user confirms
- Match verification to risk: XSS/file/audio/AI paths need an explicit threat note in the response

## Privacy defaults (governance)

- No new analytics/telemetry without explicit user request + consent story
- No logging of PII, transcripts, audio, or API keys to console in production paths
- Prefer local/on-device processing for AI speech features (see `ai-speech-meeting-tools.mdc`)
